# Rust Doesn't Have a Garbage Collector

This is a common misconception worth clarifying directly. **Rust has no garbage collector** — this is actually one of its defining features and primary design goals.

---

## How Rust Actually Manages Memory

Rust uses a system of **compile-time ownership rules** that the compiler enforces statically.

### The Three Core Rules

```rust
// RULE 1: Every value has a single owner
let s = String::from("hello");  // s owns this string

// RULE 2: There can only be one owner at a time
let s2 = s;                     // ownership MOVES to s2
// println!("{}", s);           // COMPILE ERROR - s is no longer valid

// RULE 3: When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped
{
    let s3 = String::from("world");
    // s3 is valid here
}
// s3 is GONE - memory freed automatically, no GC needed
```

### Borrowing (Temporary References)

```rust
fn print_length(s: &String) {  // borrow, don't take ownership
    println!("Length: {}", s.len());
}

fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello");
    print_length(&s);           // pass a reference
    println!("{}", s);          // s still valid - we only borrowed it
}
```

### Borrow Rules (Enforced at Compile Time)

```rust
let mut s = String::from("hello");

// You can have EITHER:
// - Any number of immutable references
let r1 = &s;
let r2 = &s;
println!("{} {}", r1, r2);  // OK

// - OR exactly ONE mutable reference
let r3 = &mut s;
// let r4 = &mut s;  // COMPILE ERROR - can't have two mutable borrows
```

